  "case_id": "D2N200",
  "method": "medsum_ent",
  "template": "soap",
  "summary_text": "S:\nThe patient reports a long-standing history of high blood pressure, taking chlorthalidone intermittently due to stomach upset. He experiences throbbing headaches, often located on the top of his head, which are sometimes accompanied by dizziness and blurry vision. He admits to taking Tylenol for the headaches, which provides some relief. He also reports occasional nausea. He has been eating a lot of McDonald's, including large fries, and admits to eating a lot of his kids' Easter candy over the weekend, which may have contributed to his elevated blood sugar levels. He reports forgetting to take his medications frequently.\n\nO:\nBlood pressure was recorded at 172/98 mmHg this morning. The patient's heart rate is 78 bpm and regular. Oxygen saturation is 98% on room air. A one plus pitting edema is noted bilaterally on the lower extremities. A two out of six systolic ejection murmur is auscultated. Lung sounds are clear bilaterally. The patient's skin is warm and dry. Neurological exam is unremarkable.\n\nA:\nThe patient presents with uncontrolled hypertension and elevated blood glucose levels. The headache and dizziness are likely related to the elevated blood pressure and potentially the hyperglycemia. Further investigation is needed to determine the underlying cause of the hypertension and hyperglycemia and to optimize treatment.\n\nP:\nI will continue the patient's current medication regimen of chlorthalidone. I will increase the metformin dosage to 1500 mg daily. I will recommend a referral to a registered dietitian for dietary counseling to reduce sodium intake. I will also recommend that the patient monitor his blood pressure three times a week at home and provide a blood pressure monitor. I will schedule a follow-up appointment in one month to assess the patient's blood pressure and blood glucose levels and to adjust the treatment plan as needed. I will also schedule a follow-up appointment in one month to assess the patient's blood pressure and blood glucose levels and to adjust the treatment plan as needed.",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nHeadache and high blood pressure.\n\nREVIEW OF SYSTEMS\n\nRespiratory: Denies shortness of breath.\nCardiovascular: Denies chest pain.\nNeurological: Reports blurry vision, dizziness, and headaches.\n\nVITALS\n\nBlood pressure today was 172/98. Oxygenation is within normal limits.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nNeck\n- General Examination: No jugular venous distention. No carotid bruits.\n\nRespiratory\n- Auscultation of Lungs: Clear bilaterally.\n\nCardiovascular\n- Auscultation of Heart: Regular rate. Slight 2/6 systolic ejection murmur, unchanged from last year.\n\nMusculoskeletal\n- Examination: Slight edema to bilateral upper extremities. 1+ pitting edema noted in the bilateral lower extremities.\n\nASSESSMENT AND PLAN\n\n1. Hypertension, uncontrolled.\n- Medical Reasoning: The patient's blood pressure is is elevated.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: We discussed that this could be multifactorial; for example, her diet, her medications regimen, or the medication she is currently on could be a factor in her elevated blood pressure. I encouraged the patient to take her current medication regimen today. I encouraged her to monitor her blood pressure 3 times a week. We also discussed the patient speaking to our nutritionist to help her diet. I recommended a DASH diet.\n- Medical Treatment: She will continue her current medication regimen.\n\n2. Type 2 diabetes.\n- Medical Reasoning: The patient's diabetes is uncontrolled.\n- Patient Education and Counseling: I advised the patient to continue taking her blood sugars to make sure that the change in medication is effective.\n- Medical Treatment: Increase metformin to 1500 mg.\n\nPatient Agreements: The patient understands and agrees with the recommended medical treatment plan.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nThe patient will follow up in 4 weeks.",
